\begin_layout Standard
This means that if we can figure out the distance between the projections
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 on the reference plane, we can very easily calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 A quick inspection of the diagram yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\overline{M_{P}^{\prime}M_{C}^{\prime}} & = & \overline{M_{C}^{\prime}O_{C}^{\prime}}+\overline{M_{P}^{\prime}O_{P}^{\prime}}-D\label{eq:MpMc}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Knowing 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{P}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{C}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, we can find these lengths:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\overline{M_{C}^{\prime}O_{C}^{\prime}} & = & L\tan\left(\pi+\alpha_{C}-\beta\right)\\
\overline{M_{P}^{\prime}O_{P}^{\prime}} & = & L\tan\alpha_{P}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
